Date:  0/0/1898
Source:  Contributions to the Early History of New Zealand
Author:  HOCKEN
Vol / Page:  140
Edition:
Quote:  For the government of the Colony as a whole there were constituted the two Houses which at present exist - the Legislative Council and the House of Representatives, together constituting the General Assembly. The councillors were nominated by the Governor, in this respect resembling the old nominee system. They held their seats for life. As showing the fear and detestation in which the word `nominee' was held, Mr. Fox and others who assisted in passing the measure viewed the relating clauses as the great blots of the Act.
Notes:

